default7.0 default              defaultWdefaulthat alternatives to sponsored academy status should be offered to failing primary schools?default&#xa0;
default7.1
default              
defaultPartnerships, federations or better support from the local authority are measures that have worked in the past. 
default&#xa0;
default7.2 
default              
defaultThere was much talk of successful academies sponsoring failing schools, but so many of these academies do not seem interested in helping other schools with large numbers of pupils
default eligible for Free School Meals or with Special Educational Needs 
defaultor 
defaultschools 
defaultlocated in poorer areas.
default&#xa0;
default7.3
default              
defaultOne 
defaultlocal secondary academy 
defaulttrust 
defaulthas recently taken over a “failing” primary school. It has turned it around from an undersubscribed junior school, with nearly one third of its students qualifying for Free School Meals, into an oversubscribed primary academy with its latest intake of 30 pupils including just ONE pupil eligible for FSM.  
defaultThe academy trust 
defaultcould have given prefer
defaultence to FSM children in its local secondary academy’s 
defaultand its sponsored primary academy’s admission arrangements. It did not. Instead it chose to give feeder status 
defaultfor admissions to the “outstanding” secondary academy 
defaultto that primary academy. Almost overnight the sponsored 
defaultprimary 
defaultacademy “improved” by becoming oversubscribed in its admissions. Pupils there are now guaranteed a place at the successful secondary academy.
default Has there been 
defaultan improvement in teaching or educational outcomes at
default the primary academy? It is too early to know.
default But certainly, it does not appear that many FSM children will benefit if there has been.
